Traditionally the way pay works at an investment bank is that, at senior le=
vels, most of your pay is in the form of a variable=C2=A0end-of-year bonus.=
 If you and your group and your firm all have a good year, you will get a l=
arge bonus, many multiples of your base salary. If you or your group or you=
r firm have a bad year, you will get a smaller bonus. If your bonus is zero=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0if your only pay for the year is your base salary =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0then you will feel deeply aggrieved and throw a huge tantrum, and als=
o odds are you=E2=80=99re getting fired. This is the traditional approach t=
o things, and it has fallen out of favor a bit since the 2008 financial cri=
sis, but it is still a useful rough model.The problem here is that variable=
 compensation has sort of asymmetric effects on happiness and loyalty. If y=
ou get paid $4 million one year and $5 million the next, you will probably =
be happy both years. You got paid a lot in absolute terms, and your pay wen=
t up year over year. If in Year 1 you took out an expensive mortgage, in Ye=
ar 2 you can pay it easily.If you get paid $5 million one year and $4 milli=
on the next, though, you will be very sad the second year. Your pay went do=
wn year-over-year, suggesting that your employer either (1) does not apprec=
iate your efforts or (2) is not in a financial position to reward them appr=
opriately. Neither is a good sign for your long-term relationship. If in Ye=
ar 1 you took out an expensive mortgage, in Year 2 finances will feel a bit=
 tight. =E2=80=9CYou knew your pay was completely variable, why did you tak=
e out an expensive mortgage,=E2=80=9D is perhaps a reasonable question, but=
 you don=E2=80=99t want to hear it. After all, you keep getting better at y=
our job; you are more experienced and have deeper client relationships and =
are more senior and taking on more responsibility. Why should you get paid=
=C2=A0less=C2=A0this year than last year? =E2=80=9CBecause the bank had a w=
orse year=E2=80=9D is a fine, correct answer, but it is not emotionally sat=
isfying. You might quit in a huff.This makes really good years particularly=
 tricky for a bank. If the bank pays out huge bonuses at the peak of the bo=
om, then the next year everyone will be disappointed and quit in huffs. (Th=
ough the poor job market that year might limit the losses.)=C2=A0If it=C2=
=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0do that =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it holds back some money =
so as not to set expectations too high, and so as to have some more money i=
n reserve to pay bonuses next year =E2=80=94=C2=A0then everyone will feel u=
nderpaid versus their competitors at other banks who do pay everything out,=
 and they=E2=80=99ll quit now for a competitor.=C2=A0There is not really an=
 easy way around this =E2=80=94 and highly variable compensation is basical=
ly good for the bank=E2=80=99s financial resilience and for the employees=
=E2=80=99 incentives =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I suppose one easy-ish way around i=
t is to pay bankers huge bonuses in really good years, but include a little=
 note with the huge bonus saying =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t get used to it.=E2=
=80=9D The note doesn=E2=80=99t really contain any information they didn=E2=
=80=99t already know =E2=80=94=C2=A0their pay is variable, a huge payout in=
 a good year guarantees nothing for next year, don=E2=80=99t take out a mor=
tgage based on this year=E2=80=99s bonus, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=
=99s still worth reminding them.So,  sure:The top 1% at Goldman Sachs Group=
 Inc. is set to receive a special one-time reward in addition to annual bon=
uses, recognizing the Wall Street titan=E2=80=99s roaring success through t=
he pandemic.The unusual payments to partners -- the roughly 400 executives =
who fill out the investment bank=E2=80=99s highest rung -- will add million=
s of dollars to many compensation packages, according to people with knowle=
dge of the matter, who asked not to be identified discussing internal decis=
ions. That group is already in line for larger payouts that range from a fe=
w million dollars to multiples of that after a year of record earnings.Gold=
man=E2=80=99s management, under pressure to fend off increasingly aggressiv=
e poaching on Wall Street, views the extra boosts as a creative solution th=
at will come with a warning: Recipients shouldn=E2=80=99t mistake the bumps=
 as part of a new pay floor, two of the people said. When compensation is s=
et next year, managers will ignore the one-time payouts when making compari=
sons.So if you get paid a $1 million salary and a $5 million bonus and a $5=
 million other bonus for 2021, and then in 2022 you get $7 million, you wil=
l say =E2=80=9Cwhat the heck, last year I got $11 million and now you are c=
utting me to $7 million,=E2=80=9D and your boss will say =E2=80=9Cno, last =
year you got $6 million and now I am raising you to $7 million, congratulat=
ions.=E2=80=9D And your boss will technically be right even though you=C2=
=A0did=C2=A0get $11 million last year, because some of it didn=E2=80=99t co=
unt. And you will grumble a little less because you=C2=A0were=C2=A0warned.M=
eanwhile in stakeholder capitalism, Goldman  announced earnings this mornin=
g:Goldman Sachs Group Inc. equities traders posted a decline in the fourth =
quarter, adding to evidence that the frenzied activity touched off by the p=
andemic is cooling, even as the bank ratcheted up payouts for employees. Th=
e company=E2=80=99s shares tumbled.Revenue from the bank=E2=80=99s trading =
operation slid 7%, missing analysts=E2=80=99 estimates for a small gain. Th=
e surprise letdown came from its equities business, which declined 11%, acc=
ording to a statement Tuesday. Despite rounding off their best year ever fo=
r both revenue and earnings, Goldman executives will need to address invest=
or concerns that the trading business is on a downward trajectory.Compensat=
ion and benefits, the single biggest driver of expenses at Goldman, jumped =
33% to $17.7 billion in 2021, an indication of big rewards for employees af=
ter a record year. ...The trading boom set off by the market volatility of =
Covid-19 might be starting to fade, and companies are having to contend wit=
h higher costs to prevent employees from defecting. That leaves bank leader=
s with the task of resetting expectations.The classic defense of=C2=A0share=
holder=C2=A0capitalism goes something like =E2=80=9Cshareholders are the re=
sidual claimants on the cash flows of the corporation, while every other st=
akeholder has some contractual relationship with the company, so directors =
and managers should have fiduciary duties to those residual claimants.=E2=
=80=9D But anyone who has worked at a bank knows that the shareholders are =
not the only residual claimants. The employees get their cut too.
