My  general view of the =E2=80=9Crevolving door=E2=80=9D is that it is good=
 for regulators to get a reputation for being tough in high-profile cases, =
because that will make them more attractive to the private sector. If you a=
re a regulator with a reputation for being tough, then:=09Potential private=
-sector employers will think that you=E2=80=99re a creative hardworking go-=
getter, because those characteristics tend to correlate=C2=A0with toughness=
 in regulation.=C2=A0=09Potential private-sector employers will have=C2=A0m=
ore need to hire ex-regulators, because regulation is tougher so there is m=
ore work to do to respond to it, and ex-regulators are particularly=C2=A0qu=
alified to do that work.=09Other employees at your regulator=C2=A0will resp=
ect your=C2=A0toughness, and so when you go into private practice and advoc=
ate for a client to those regulators, they will take you seriously and be i=
nclined to go easier on your clients; private-sector employers understand t=
his.=09Potential private-sector employers will want to hire you at a high s=
alary because=C2=A0then you will stop being a regulator, and if you are tou=
gh on them as a regulator it is worth paying you to stop.=C2=A0Of course yo=
u can take this too far. If you develop a reputation for being unreasonable=
 or unprofessional or dishonest in your pursuit of tough regulatory action,=
 private-sector employers will be less interested in hiring you. Or=C2=A0if=
 you conduct a perfectly reasonable and  honestly rather gentle investigati=
on into a hilariously thin-skinned billionaire=C2=A0this might happen:A par=
tner at law firm Cooley LLP got an unexpected call late last year from a la=
wyer for one of the firm=E2=80=99s most famous clients, Elon Musk=E2=80=99s=
 Tesla Inc., with an ultimatum.The world=E2=80=99s richest man wanted Coole=
y, which was representing Tesla in numerous lawsuits, to fire one of its at=
torneys or it would lose the electric-vehicle company=E2=80=99s business, p=
eople familiar with the matter said.The target of Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s ire wa=
s a former U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission lawyer whom Cooley had h=
ired for its securities litigation and enforcement practice and who had no =
involvement in the firm=E2=80=99s work for Tesla. At the SEC, the attorney =
had interviewed Mr. Musk during the agency=E2=80=99s investigation of the T=
esla chief executive=E2=80=99s 2018 tweet claiming, wrongly, to have secure=
d funding to potentially take the electric-vehicle maker private. =E2=80=A6=
Cooley has declined to fire the attorney, who remains an associate at the f=
irm, the people said. Since early December, Tesla has begun taking steps in=
 several cases to replace Cooley or add additional counsel, legal documents=
 show. Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s rocket company Space Exploration Technologies Cor=
p., also known as SpaceX, has stopped using Cooley for regulatory work, acc=
ording to people familiar with the matter.One assumes that Musk was operati=
ng out of pure emotional grudge here, but I suppose it=E2=80=99s worth aski=
ng if that phone call was a good strategic move.=C2=A0Of course=C2=A0Cooley=
 can=E2=80=99t actually fire the associate, which would be disastrous for i=
ts reputation. But that=E2=80=99s not the goal here. Other law firms that d=
o a bunch of work with Tesla might have to ask prospective hires, like, =E2=
=80=9Chey you haven=E2=80=99t done anything to annoy Elon Musk have you?=E2=
=80=9D And so current government regulators=C2=A0might think =E2=80=9Chmm, =
I should go easy on Elon Musk so he doesn=E2=80=99t ruin my future career.=
=E2=80=9DBut, look, if a regulator started an investigation into Elon Musk,=
 and Musk called her up and said =E2=80=9Cdo you know who I am, I will ruin=
 your career,=E2=80=9D that would definitely make things=C2=A0worse=C2=A0fo=
r him, don=E2=80=99t you think? Like she=E2=80=99d tell her bosses and they=
=E2=80=99d throw the book at him, add charges of interfering with an invest=
igation, etc. Threatening to ruin a regulator=E2=80=99s career for investig=
ating you is a very bad look! Of course Musk didn=E2=80=99t do that. Instea=
d he actually tried to ruin a regulator=E2=80=99s career=C2=A0for investiga=
ting him. Arguably that=E2=80=99s a smarter move? Like, the Cooley associat=
e is no longer at the SEC and that investigation is closed, so Musk=E2=80=
=99s direct risk is lower.And yet =E2=80=A6=C2=A0if you=E2=80=99re at the S=
EC=C2=A0now, and you=E2=80=99re conducting a different investigation of Tes=
la, wouldn=E2=80=99t this make you want to be tougher on him? Or if you=E2=
=80=99re at the Justice Department, or some other government agency? His od=
ds of actually ruining your career are low; there are a lot of law firms, m=
ost of them don=E2=80=99t work with Tesla, and Musk didn=E2=80=99t even suc=
ceed in getting this associate fired. As a matter of regulatory solidarity,=
 and of punishing Musk for trying to intimidate regulators, wouldn=E2=80=99=
t you go a bit harder now?
