<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Non-precedential comp</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traditionally the way pay works at an =
investment bank is that, at senior levels, most of your pay is in the form =
of a variable=C2=A0end-of-year bonus. If you and your group and your firm a=
ll have a good year, you will get a large bonus, many multiples of your bas=
e salary. If you or your group or your firm have a bad year, you will get a=
 smaller bonus. If your bonus is zero =E2=80=94=C2=A0if your only pay for t=
he year is your base salary =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you will feel deeply aggrie=
ved and throw a huge tantrum, and also odds are you=E2=80=99re getting fire=
d. This is the traditional approach to things, and it has <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26404004.266632/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZWJ=
hLmV1cm9wYS5ldS9zaXRlcy9kZWZhdWx0L2RvY3VtZW50cy9maWxlcy9kb2N1bWVudHMvMTAxOD=
AvMTMxNDgzOS8xYjBmM2Y5OS1mOTEzLTQ2MWEtYjNlOS1mYTAwNjRiMTk0NmIvRUJBLUdMLTIwM=
TUtMjIlMjBGaW5hbCUyMHJlcG9ydCUyMG9uJTIwR3VpZGVsaW5lcyUyMG9uJTIwU291bmQlMjBS=
ZW11bmVyYXRpb24lMjBQb2xpY2llcy5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa7899919" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">fallen out of favor a bit</a> since the 2008 financial crisis, but it i=
s still a useful rough model.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem h=
ere is that variable compensation has sort of asymmetric effects on happine=
ss and loyalty. If you get paid $4 million one year and $5 million the next=
, you will probably be happy both years. You got paid a lot in absolute ter=
ms, and your pay went up year over year. If in Year 1 you took out an expen=
sive mortgage, in Year 2 you can pay it easily.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">If you get paid $5 million one year and $4 million the next, though, y=
ou will be very sad the second year. Your pay went down year-over-year, sug=
gesting that your employer either (1) does not appreciate your efforts or (=
2) is not in a financial position to reward them appropriately. Neither is =
a good sign for your long-term relationship. If in Year 1 you took out an e=
xpensive mortgage, in Year 2 finances will feel a bit tight. =E2=80=9CYou k=
new your pay was completely variable, why did you take out an expensive mor=
tgage,=E2=80=9D is perhaps a reasonable question, but you don=E2=80=99t wan=
t to hear it. After all, you keep getting better at your job; you are more =
experienced and have deeper client relationships and are more senior and ta=
king on more responsibility. Why should you get paid=C2=A0<em>less=C2=A0</e=
m>this year than last year? =E2=80=9CBecause the bank had a worse year=E2=
=80=9D is a fine, correct answer, but it is not emotionally satisfying. You=
 might quit in a huff.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This makes really go=
od years particularly tricky for a bank. If the bank pays out huge bonuses =
at the peak of the boom, then the next year everyone will be disappointed a=
nd quit in huffs. (Though the poor job market that year might limit the los=
ses.)=C2=A0If it=C2=A0<em>doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>do that =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
if it holds back some money so as not to set expectations too high, and so =
as to have some more money in reserve to pay bonuses next year =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0then everyone will feel underpaid versus their competitors at other bank=
s who do pay everything out, and they=E2=80=99ll quit now for a competitor.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is not really an easy way arou=
nd this =E2=80=94 and highly variable compensation is basically good for th=
e bank=E2=80=99s financial resilience and for the employees=E2=80=99 incent=
ives =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I suppose one easy-ish way around it is to pay bank=
ers huge bonuses in really good years, but include a little note with the h=
uge bonus saying =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t get used to it.=E2=80=9D The note d=
oesn=E2=80=99t really contain any information they didn=E2=80=99t already k=
now =E2=80=94=C2=A0their pay is variable, a huge payout in a good year guar=
antees nothing for next year, don=E2=80=99t take out a mortgage based on th=
is year=E2=80=99s bonus, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s still worth r=
eminding them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So, <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26404004.266632/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMTQvZ29sZG1hbi1zLW1vc3QtZWxpdGUtcmFua=
y10by1nZXQtbWlsbGlvbnMtaW4tb25lLXRpbWUtcGF5b3V0cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTE4MjJfTU9O=
RVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0=
yMjAxMTgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB33a23855"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> sure</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The top 1% =
at Goldman Sachs Group Inc. is set to receive a special one-time reward in =
addition to annual bonuses, recognizing the Wall Street titan=E2=80=99s roa=
ring success through the pandemic.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The unus=
ual payments to partners -- the roughly 400 executives who fill out the inv=
estment bank=E2=80=99s highest rung -- will add millions of dollars to many=
 compensation packages, according to people with knowledge of the matter, w=
ho asked not to be identified discussing internal decisions. That group is =
already in line for larger payouts that range from a few million dollars to=
 multiples of that after a year of record earnings.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Goldman=E2=80=99s management, under pressure to fend off increasin=
gly aggressive poaching on Wall Street, views the extra boosts as a creativ=
e solution that will come with a warning: Recipients shouldn=E2=80=99t mist=
ake the bumps as part of a new pay floor, two of the people said. When comp=
ensation is set next year, managers will ignore the one-time payouts when m=
aking comparisons.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So if you g=
et paid a $1 million salary and a $5 million bonus and a $5 million other b=
onus for 2021, and then in 2022 you get $7 million, you will say =E2=80=9Cw=
hat the heck, last year I got $11 million and now you are cutting me to $7 =
million,=E2=80=9D and your boss will say =E2=80=9Cno, last year you got $6 =
million and now I am raising you to $7 million, congratulations.=E2=80=9D A=
nd your boss will technically be right even though you=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</=
em>get $11 million last year, because some of it didn=E2=80=99t count. And =
you will grumble a little less because you=C2=A0<em>were=C2=A0</em>warned.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile in stakeholder capitalism, Goldma=
n <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26404004.266632/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMTgvZ29sZG1=
hbi1zLXRyYWRpbmctZGl2aXNpb24tc2xpcHMtd2l0aC1wYW5kZW1pYy1ib29zdC1jb29saW5nLW=
9mZj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTE4MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY=
2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAxMTgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8cb2fb20" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> announced earnings this morning</a>=
:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Goldman Sachs Group Inc. equi=
ties traders posted a decline in the fourth quarter, adding to evidence tha=
t the frenzied activity touched off by the pandemic is cooling, even as the=
 bank ratcheted up payouts for employees. The company=E2=80=99s shares tumb=
led.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Revenue from the bank=E2=80=99s tradin=
g operation slid 7%, missing analysts=E2=80=99 estimates for a small gain. =
The surprise letdown came from its equities business, which declined 11%, a=
ccording to a statement Tuesday. Despite rounding off their best year ever =
for both revenue and earnings, Goldman executives will need to address inve=
stor concerns that the trading business is on a downward trajectory.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Compensation and benefits, the single biggest dri=
ver of expenses at Goldman, jumped 33% to $17.7 billion in 2021, an indicat=
ion of big rewards for employees after a record year. ...</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">The trading boom set off by the market volatility of Covid-1=
9 might be starting to fade, and companies are having to contend with highe=
r costs to prevent employees from defecting. That leaves bank leaders with =
the task of resetting expectations.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">The classic defense of=C2=A0<em>shareholder=C2=A0</em>capitalism goes=
 something like =E2=80=9Cshareholders are the residual claimants on the cas=
h flows of the corporation, while every other stakeholder has some contract=
ual relationship with the company, so directors and managers should have fi=
duciary duties to those residual claimants.=E2=80=9D But anyone who has wor=
ked at a bank knows that the shareholders are not the only residual claiman=
ts. The employees get their cut too.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad"=
 border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"center">
